@flexiarg t3/architectural-pair
@title Architectural Pair
@sigils [🏛️/构]
@audience programme-architects, institutional-leads, funders
@tone formal-analytic
@style design-pattern
@part Open Research Training
@up t3/transformation-space
@see t3/co-ownership-engine, t3/feedback-activation-loop, t3/capability-not-functioning
@next t3/implementation-modes
@length 180-260
@allow-new-claims false

! conclusion:
  Whether training inputs translate into sustained collective practice depends on the institutional architecture that receives them — specifically, whether structures exist to convert individual participation into shared stewardship and to generate evidence of impact that routes back to practitioners and decision-makers. These architectural conditions are both the most important determinants of normalisation and the least developed in the programme studied.

  + context: The systematic weakness of NPT's Collective Action and Reflexive Monitoring domains in the T3 data points beyond input quality to the institutional structures that determine whether training normalises.
  + if: You want training to produce collective, sustained practice change rather than individual, fragile goodwill.
  + however: Architecture-level improvements require changes to the institutional environment — workload models, feedback systems, co-ownership pathways — that the programme can advocate for but cannot unilaterally enact.
  + then: Prioritise the architectural pair: design co-ownership structures that convert participation into shared stewardship, and feedback systems that generate visible evidence of impact. Recognise that these require institutional partnership, not just programme redesign.
  + because: Without architecture, training inputs are absorbed by individual effort and decay when that effort is withdrawn; with architecture, the same inputs are multiplied into institutional capacity.
      + mechanism: Co-ownership creates distributed maintenance of the practice; feedback creates the evidence base that justifies institutional investment in maintaining the architecture.
      + counterfactual: If both patterns remain weak, even excellent training produces the "absorbed input" mode — individual goodwill carrying an unsupported practice.
      + applies-when: The programme operates across institutions with no guaranteed local infrastructure for sustaining training outcomes.
      + does-not-apply: Institutions that already have functioning feedback and co-ownership structures for training programmes.
      + signals: Trainers report isolation after the programme ends; formal sharing channels go unused; impact evidence is anecdotal or absent.
      + evidence: Feedback-Activation Loop — COM-B item "effects are being measured" M=3.35 (lowest across all waves); Co-Ownership Engine — qualitative evidence of sustained engagement only where co-ownership was present (T1 t1-19, T1 t1-25, T3 t3-4).
  + next-steps:
      - Map current co-ownership and feedback infrastructure at participating institutions.
      - Identify minimal viable architectural interventions that do not depend on institutional mandate.
      - Test whether participatory evaluation designs (Corneli, 2023) can close the feedback loop using the programme's own open research practices.
  + governance:
      - practice: assess architectural capacity alongside intervention quality in programme reviews.
      - metric: proportion of trainers contributing back within 6 months; proportion of sessions with structured feedback beyond optional surveys.
